      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>29</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008I/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>008I</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/008I/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Compound sentences">Compound sentences</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>        That's what an intuitionistic model is: a frame, plus a set of atomics chosen for each point in the frame, such that whenever <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x R y]]></fr:tex> in the frame, the set assigned to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is a subset of the set assigned to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>29</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008J/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>008J</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/008J/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Intuitionistic model">Intuitionistic model</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>An <html:strong>intuitionistic model</html:strong> is a <fr:link href="/lectures/008F/" title="Frame, point, reachable" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/008F/" display-uri="008F" type="local">frame</fr:link>, plus a <fr:link href="/lectures/008H/" title="Valuation on a frame" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/008H/" display-uri="008H" type="local">valuation on that frame</fr:link>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>On this basis, we can calculate values for every formula of our language at every point in the model.
        Here's how.
</html:p>
            <html:p>        As before, for any <html:em>atomic</html:em> sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, we will have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = Y]]></fr:tex> if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is a member of the set assigned to the point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in the model <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>.
        For compound sentences, we proceed by way of the main connective of the sentence.
        I'll discuss <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land , \lor , \top , \bot ]]></fr:tex> first, since those are simpler; I'll put off <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg , \rightarrow ]]></fr:tex> for now.</html:p>
            <html:p>            No matter what model <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> we're in, and no matter what point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> we're at inside the model <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>:
            <html:ul><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \land  B, x) = Y]]></fr:tex> if both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = Y]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(B, x) = Y]]></fr:tex>, and otherwise <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \land  B, x) = ?]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
            <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \lor  B, x) = ?]]></fr:tex> if both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = ?]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(B, x) = ?]]></fr:tex>, and otherwise <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \lor  B, x) = Y]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
            <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\top , x) = Y]]></fr:tex>; and</html:li>
            <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\bot , x) = ?]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
            <html:p>            As you can see, this is just like the Boolean structure, but with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> playing the role of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> the role of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
            The difference of the names of the values isn't really important; it's just there to be reminiscent of a difference in how these values are often interpreted.
            For example, where our clause for conjunction in the classical case is often taken to indicate that a conjunction is <html:em>true</html:em> iff both conjuncts are true, here the corresponding clause is meant to indicate that a conjunction is <html:em>known</html:em> iff both conjuncts are known.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>29</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008K/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>008K</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/008K/</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Side note</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>This should lead you to wonder about disjunction: surely it's possible to know a disjunction without knowing either disjunct, but the clause we have here seems to rule this out.
            In fact, there is another way to proceed that would be more careful about disjunction, for just this reason; we're working this way because it's simpler, even though it strains the knowledge interpretation.
            Our method is based on what are sometimes called "Kripke models"; the more involved method would work with what are called "Beth models".
            Both kinds of model determine intuitionistic logic.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>            If that were all there was to it, though, then there would be no point in bundling up multiple points into a frame.
            Where that stuff comes into play is with the remaining connectives: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rightarrow ]]></fr:tex>.
            To give a value to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> at a point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in a model, we don't just look at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> itself.
            Instead, we look at every point that's <html:em>reachable</html:em> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in the model.
            Remember, every point is reachable from itself; so this includes looking at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>.
            But it often includes more.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> to get the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> at a point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>, what's required is that at <html:em>every</html:em> point reachable from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in the model, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> gets the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex>.
            The idea is that it's not enough in general for us to know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> just that we don't yet know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
            Something more is needed.
            What's needed is that there is <html:em>no way</html:em> to extend our knowledge where we could come to know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
            Or at least, that's the idea that these models go with.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            The idea for implication is similar.
            Again, to give a value to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \rightarrow  B]]></fr:tex> at a point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in a model <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>, we look at every point reachable from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>.
            For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \rightarrow  B]]></fr:tex> to get the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, what's required is this: that there's no way to extend our knowledge to know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> without also knowing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.
            That is, we require that every point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> reachable from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, y)= Y]]></fr:tex> also gives us <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(B, y) = Y]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            Let's look at some examples, using a new example model, which I'l call <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>:
</html:p>
            <html:p>
              <fr:resource hash="9df6136b00cbf1cc12f4ea692bb0bf55">
                <fr:resource-content>
                  <html:img src="/lectures/9df6136b00cbf1cc12f4ea692bb0bf55.svg" />
                </fr:resource-content>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}]]></fr:resource-source>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
            \begin {tikzcd}
                &1: \{p, q, r, s, t\}\\
                &2: \{p, q, r, s\} \arrow [u]\\
                3: \{p, q\}\arrow [ur]&&4: \{p, r\}\arrow [ul]\\
                &5: \{p\}\arrow [ul]\arrow [ur]\\
            \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:resource-source>
              </fr:resource>
            </html:p>
            <html:p>
            Here, I've indicated the valuation along with the frame, by putting at each point the set of atomic sentences assigned to that point.
            Here are some example calculations of values of various compound sentences at points in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>:
            <html:ul><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\neg  q, 5) = ?]]></fr:tex>.
                Even though we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(q, 5) = ?]]></fr:tex>, the fact that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(q, 3) = Y]]></fr:tex>, together with the fact that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[5 R 3]]></fr:tex>, forces this result.</html:li>
                <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\neg  u, 2) = Y]]></fr:tex>.
                Here, we have two points we need to check: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>.
                Since both of these points assign the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> to the atomic sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex>, we have this result.</html:li>
                <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(q \rightarrow  r, 5) = ?]]></fr:tex>.
                Since we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(q, 3) = Y]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(r, 3) = ?]]></fr:tex>, this result follows.</html:li>
                <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(r \rightarrow  q, 5) = ?]]></fr:tex>.
                Since we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(r, 4) = Y]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(q, 4) = ?]]></fr:tex>, this result follows.</html:li>
                <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M((q \rightarrow  r) \lor  (r \rightarrow  q), 5) = ?]]></fr:tex>.
                We've seen that both of the components of this disjunction take value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[5]]></fr:tex>, so the disjunction does as well.


<html:p>                Note what's happened here: we've got a reflection at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[5]]></fr:tex> of what's going on at both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[3]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[4]]></fr:tex>: in particular, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[3]]></fr:tex> gives us <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> without <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[4]]></fr:tex> gives us <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> without <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>.
                Our connectives are giving us a way to "look around" inside the model, in a limited way.
</html:p></html:li>

<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M((q \land  r) \rightarrow  s, 5) = Y]]></fr:tex>.
                Here, we need to check every point, since every point is reachable from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[5]]></fr:tex>.
                What we see is that there are only two points that give the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>\ to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \land  r]]></fr:tex>; these are <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>.
                And both of these points also give the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>.
                So we have the result.</html:li>
                
                <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M((q \land  r) \rightarrow  t, 5) = ?]]></fr:tex>.
                Again, we check every point, and see that just <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> give the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>\ to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \land  r]]></fr:tex>.
                This time, though, one of them (viz <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex>) gives <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> to the consequent <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t]]></fr:tex>.
                So we get this result instead.</html:li>
                <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M((q \land  r) \rightarrow  t, 2) = ?]]></fr:tex>.
                This time we only need to look at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>, but since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> still gives <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to the antecedent and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> to the consequent, it's the same result.</html:li>
                <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M((q \land  r) \rightarrow  t, 1) = Y]]></fr:tex>.
                Here, we only need to look at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> itself, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> is the only point reachable from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>.
                And here, we have the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> for both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  q]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t]]></fr:tex>.
                So we get this result.</html:li>
                <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\neg  ((q \land  r) \rightarrow  t), 2) = ?]]></fr:tex>.
                Here, we look at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>, since these are the points reachable from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>.
                At each of these, we ask: what is the value of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(q \land  r) \rightarrow  t]]></fr:tex> here?
                As we've seen, it's <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex>.
                So we have this result.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
            <html:p>Let's wrap all this up in a definition for later reference:</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>29</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008L/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>008L</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/008L/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Evaluating sentences in intuitionistic models">Evaluating sentences in intuitionistic models</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Given an <fr:link href="/lectures/008J/" title="Intuitionistic model" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/008J/" display-uri="008J" type="local">intuitionistic model</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> and a point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in it, we assign values to every sentence at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in the model as follows:
<html:ul><html:li>atomic: for any atomic sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = Y]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is in the set of atomic sentences assigned to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> by the model, and otherwise <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = ?]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
<html:li>conjunction: for any sentences <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \land  B, x) = Y]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = M(B, x) = Y]]></fr:tex>, and otherwise <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \land  B, x) = ?]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
<html:li>disjunction: for any sentences <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \lor  B, x) = ?]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = M(B, x) = ?]]></fr:tex>, and otherwise <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \lor  B, x) = Y]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
<html:li>verum and falsum: always, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\top , x) = Y]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\bot , x) = vQ]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
<html:li>negation: for any sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\neg  A, x) = Y]]></fr:tex> iff every point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> reachable from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, y) = vQ]]></fr:tex>; otherwise, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\neg  A, x) = vQ]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
<html:li>implication: for any sentences <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \rightarrow  B, x) = vQ]]></fr:tex> iff there is some point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> reachable from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, y) = Y]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(B, y) = ?]]></fr:tex>; otherwise <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \rightarrow  B, x)]]></fr:tex> = <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" hidden-when-empty="true">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:authors />
        <fr:title text="Backlinks">Backlinks</fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>29</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008L/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>008L</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/008L/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Evaluating sentences in intuitionistic models">Evaluating sentences in intuitionistic models</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Given an <fr:link href="/lectures/008J/" title="Intuitionistic model" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/008J/" display-uri="008J" type="local">intuitionistic model</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> and a point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in it, we assign values to every sentence at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in the model as follows:
<html:ul><html:li>atomic: for any atomic sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = Y]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is in the set of atomic sentences assigned to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> by the model, and otherwise <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = ?]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
<html:li>conjunction: for any sentences <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \land  B, x) = Y]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = M(B, x) = Y]]></fr:tex>, and otherwise <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \land  B, x) = ?]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
<html:li>disjunction: for any sentences <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \lor  B, x) = ?]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = M(B, x) = ?]]></fr:tex>, and otherwise <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \lor  B, x) = Y]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
<html:li>verum and falsum: always, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\top , x) = Y]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\bot , x) = vQ]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
<html:li>negation: for any sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\neg  A, x) = Y]]></fr:tex> iff every point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> reachable from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, y) = vQ]]></fr:tex>; otherwise, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(\neg  A, x) = vQ]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
<html:li>implication: for any sentences <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \rightarrow  B, x) = vQ]]></fr:tex> iff there is some point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> reachable from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, y) = Y]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(B, y) = ?]]></fr:tex>; otherwise <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A \rightarrow  B, x)]]></fr:tex> = <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
