            <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008F/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>008F</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/008F/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Frame, point, reachable">Frame, point, reachable</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A <html:strong>frame</html:strong> is some set of things, called <html:strong>points</html:strong>, with some arrows between them, in any configuration.
(We usually use numbers for points, but that's not very important; it's just convenient.)

All that matters about a frame is which points are <html:em>reachable</html:em> from which points.
Every point can reach itself, plus points can reach along any arrows in the frame, and they can follow chains of arrows: anywhere that a particular point can reach in this way is <html:strong>reachable</html:strong> from that starting point.
(Any reaching along an arrow or along a chain of arrows must follow the direction of all the arrows in question.)</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
